Rounding up my thoughts about our Seoul trip... Before we flew, I was getting burnt out at work and stressed over what most Singaporeans stress over... I still probably am. I wasn't even very in the mood to pack and leave for another adventure. I just wanted to curl up somewhere alone and sleep, but trip has to be done. So off we flew.

On this 11-day trip, we got caught in the rain together, we carried each other's baggage, and he made sure everyone was okay. Mentally for me especially. Like when less than an hour on the bus out to the Alpaca Park and I started having one of my panic attacks that came with the excessive burping/vomiting feeling. Long didn't simply say let's get down and go back or anything like that. He just gave me a long look as if to say "the wave will pass... or else you tell me what you want me to do" and it did go away. Or when I kept panting and dramatically saying I'm dying and wanna go back down when we went up to Sunrise Peak. Both of them kept saying "C'mon!!! Almost there liao!" We were tired - nagging, scolding, persuading Little Foot and repeating ourselves many times. And she kept asking to be carried. There was also very little she could eat. Everything we asked if it was not spicy turned out to be some sort of spicy ğŸ˜“. So she survived on seaweed, deskinned fried chicken, fries, biscuits, cakes and milk. And sugared drinks. The only highlight for her was Korean BBQ, which she had 2x. We had to make do. As a mother I felt bad... but she came back half a kg heavier and 1cm taller. So I should cut myself some slack.
It was still quality time spent together. We had many bloopers, missed our train station, laughed at each other, arrowed each other to wash milk bottles, found each other's hands in the crowds.
I think we did well, even if we still missed out on many things. Perhaps we should go back when the kiddo is older and able to eat a bit of spicy food.
